post_text: We are very proud of our very own Heather Strait!
shared_text:
Discovery Station
April 30 at 12:44 PM ·

We are pleased to announce our next Discovery Station Covid19 Hero Award Winner: Heather Strait.

Heather was nominated by Terri Rader for her work as a teacher at McConnellsburg Area High School.

"Heather is continuing to provide high-quality life skills instruction to her students. She makes videos of cooking lessons for her students to watch and follow. She provides videos of strategies to help them relax including a video of her family dancing. She is currently searching for fun Earth Day activities her students can do with limited materials. She has chosen to spread joy during this challenge."

Are you struggling with your Internet connection? Have you completed the Broadband Survey being conducted by the Southern Alleghenies Planning & Development Commission? If not, please do so TODAY at the link below. The survey closes soon (this weekend) and this is a great opportunity to help the region address the lack of sufficient Internet access to our rural area. Central Fulton has a representative on this committee and we are committed to helping this project move forward. Your response helps us with this goal.

Take the survey in less than 5 minutes by visiting one of the follow websites:

For Your Home: https://tinyurl.com/BroadbandHOME

For Your Business: https://tinyurl.com/BroadbandBiz

Governor Wolf has ordered all 67 counties in PA to stay-at-home. Under these new orders, we must have all student educational materials for online learning picked up today from school. The elementary school is open now until 6:00 PM. If you are a middle or high school student and have notified Mrs. Ramsey that you needed materials, the building will be open from 5:00-8:00 PM this evening. This is for EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS ONLY. This will be the last day to retrieve items until the Governor lifts the stay-at-home orders.

We appreciate your cooperation and willingness to ensure that your child’s education is continued during these uncertain times.

Please keep safe! And don’t forget to fill out your census as today is Census Day! Thank you.

Governor Wolf has announced that all school districts will close for two weeks, effective Monday, March 16th, in a response to growing concerns statewide about the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19). Tentative plans are for classes to resume on Monday, March 30th.

The school district has also canceled all practices, events, and extracurricular activities starting Saturday, March 14. As of this moment, those practices, events, and extracurriculars can reconvene on Monday, March 30.

post_text:
As the COVID-19 coronavirus continues to be a primary topic in the news, we wanted to share how this virus relates to our district and what we are doing to be prepared. The Center for Disease Control and Prevention has advised school districts to review their emergency preparedness plans, which includes responding to potential pandemic outbreaks, and we are undertaking this action.

Additional measures include:

Monitoring daily attendance for students, faculty, and staff
Daily disinfecting of student desks, classroom tables, doorknobs, faucet handles, and light switches
Keeping abreast of information found on various sources such as the Center for Disease Control, PA Department of Health, and PA Department of Education

post_text: Central Fulton School District will hold registration for the 2020-2021 school year on Thursday, March 26th, Tuesday, March 31st and Wednesday, April 1st, 2020. Children who will be age 4 on or before the first day of school (August 26th) are eligible for the K4 program and children who will be 5 on or before the first day of school are eligible for the K5 (Kindergarten) program. Please note the students who are currently enrolled in our K4 program do not need to re-register for K5. Please contact Kelli Miller at kmiller@cfsd.info or 717-485-7072 to schedule an appointment.

post_text: SAP&DC was recently awarded a grant from the Appalachian Regional Commission to complete an analysis of broadband needs in the region. The study will inventory existing broadband assets, identify gaps in service, and develop a plan for improving connectivity throughout the region. As part of the study, SAP&DC is conducting a survey to assess current levels of broadband service and needs.

post_text: NOTICE: The upcoming Central Fulton School District Committee Meetings, Work Session, and Regular Board Meeting will be postponed from their scheduled dates. post_text: Last evening, we had an adult make a threat towards adult staff at a boys intramural basketball practice. The District and the State Police take these issues very seriously and have taken necessary precautionary steps and the State Police will be monitoring the school today to ensure everyone's safety. There is no immediate danger to students or staff, but we are proceeding with an over-abundance of caution.

post_text: Today we had a large number of students both absent from the elementary school and sent home due to a fast moving stomach virus. We have consulted with local health care providers and they confirmed that they are also seeing this in their local settings. As a precaution we have disinfected all common areas and personal area surfaces in the building. Please do not send your child to school if they are experiencing stomach pain, nausea, vomiting and/or headache. We are doing all that we can to contain and eliminate further spread here at school.

post_text:
Fulton County Childcare Vocational School Preschool
will run from February 28-May 11. Children from 3-5 are encouraged to come as long as children are potty trained. Children come one day a week for the 11 weeks the preschool runs. The days of the week are Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday. The cost is $15 per child or $25 for 2 children in one household. Preschool is held at McConnellsburg High School room 14. Applications are available in the McConnellsburg High School Office or by contacting Anjuli Barber at 717-485-3195 ext. 1200 or abarber@cfsd.info.

post_text: As most of you know, we lost a dear friend and teacher this weekend. Ms. Cathy Richards touched many, many Iives in this school district over the past 34 years. On Thursday, April 21, her family will receive friends at the McConnellsburg High School Auditorium beginning at 3:00 PM, with a Life Celebration at 7:00. In order to avoid congestion of buses and visitors we will dismiss at 2:00. K4 students will dismiss at 1:00. Please continue to lift her family and friends up in thought and prayer. Again, Central Fulton School District will dismiss at 2:00 on Thursday, April 21. K4 will dismiss at 1:00. Thank you.

post_text: The McConnellsburg High School Preschool starts March 15 and runs through May 19. Hours are 8:30 to 10:15. Students go one day a week – Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday. The program is open to children ages 3 to 5. They must be potty trained and not enrolled in the school’s K-4 program. To sign up your child, or for more information, call Mrs. Barber at the school at 485-3915.

post_text: Each year, FFA chapters around the country celebrate National FFA Week. The week long tradition began in 1947 when the National FFA Board of Directors designated the week of George Washington's Birthday as National FFA Week in recognition of his legacy as an agriculturist and farmer. This coming week the McConnellsburg FFA Chapter will be celebrating with many fun activities. Don't forget to dress up each day! Monday is camo day so be wearing your best!

post_text:
On November 13, the PA Academic Review site will was fully populated with grades 3 through 8 ELA and Math as well as Algebra I and Literature. The purpose of this site is to increase awareness and understanding of our state’s Eligible Content – the grade by grade statements that define what we want our students to know and do. The state is soliciting actionable feedback on the Eligible Content as part of its review process.

Please visit http://www.paacademicreview.org and complete the brief survey. PDE needs a good cross section of educators and community to provide feedback on this information. Thus far, we have had over 5,000 hits on the site from individuals who identified themselves as Pennsylvanians.

The site is very clear and concise and it only takes a few minutes to look at the content.
